<paragraph blockId="5.[177,1085,335,445]" pageId="5" pageNumber="490">
D e s c r i p t i o n: 
<quantity box="[407,490,335,357]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.9" pageId="5" pageNumber="490" unit="mm" value="3.9">3.9 mm</quantity>
. Habitus as in 
<figureCitation box="[649,713,335,357]" captionStart="Figs 8-14" captionStartId="4.[177,217,1480,1502]" captionTargetBox="[181,1071,470,1454]" captionTargetId="figure-203@4.[177,1084,470,1467]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 8-14: Tropimenelytron schuelkei nov.sp.: (8) habitus; (9) forebody; (10) head in lateral view; (11) antenna; (12) male abdominal segments VI-VIII; (13-14) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view. Scale bars: 8: 1.0 mm; 9, 11-12: 0.5 mm; 10: 0.2 mm; 13-14: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5276229" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5276229/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="490">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
. Coloration: head dark-brown; pronotum reddish-brown; elytra yellowish-brown; abdomen reddish-brown, with the anterior 3/4 of segment 
<collectionCode box="[336,363,394,415]" country="Norway" name="Mykotektet, National Veterinary Institute" pageId="5" pageNumber="490">VI</collectionCode>
slightly darker; legs yellowish; antennae dark-brown, with the basal 3 antennomeres yellowish brown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[177,1085,460,599]" pageId="5" pageNumber="490">
Head oblong and of ovoid shape, 1.15 times as long as wide; punctation extremely fine, barely noticeable; surface with distinct microreticulation and subdued shine. Eyes small, not projecting from lateral contours of head, approximately 1/3 the length of postocular region in dorsal view (
<figureCitation box="[405,506,548,570]" captionStart="Figs 8-14" captionStartId="4.[177,217,1480,1502]" captionTargetBox="[181,1071,470,1454]" captionTargetId="figure-203@4.[177,1084,470,1467]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 8-14: Tropimenelytron schuelkei nov.sp.: (8) habitus; (9) forebody; (10) head in lateral view; (11) antenna; (12) male abdominal segments VI-VIII; (13-14) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view. Scale bars: 8: 1.0 mm; 9, 11-12: 0.5 mm; 10: 0.2 mm; 13-14: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5276229" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5276229/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="490">Figs 9-10</figureCitation>
). Antennae gradually incrassate apically, antennomere X approximately 1.5 times as wide as long (
<figureCitation box="[598,672,577,599]" captionStart="Figs 8-14" captionStartId="4.[177,217,1480,1502]" captionTargetBox="[181,1071,470,1454]" captionTargetId="figure-203@4.[177,1084,470,1467]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 8-14: Tropimenelytron schuelkei nov.sp.: (8) habitus; (9) forebody; (10) head in lateral view; (11) antenna; (12) male abdominal segments VI-VIII; (13-14) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view. Scale bars: 8: 1.0 mm; 9, 11-12: 0.5 mm; 10: 0.2 mm; 13-14: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5276229" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5276229/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="490">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[177,1085,614,695]" pageId="5" pageNumber="490">
Pronotum approximately as wide as long and 1.3 times as wide as head; maximal width in anterior half; posterior angles weakly marked (
<figureCitation box="[688,751,644,666]" captionStart="Figs 8-14" captionStartId="4.[177,217,1480,1502]" captionTargetBox="[181,1071,470,1454]" captionTargetId="figure-203@4.[177,1084,470,1467]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 8-14: Tropimenelytron schuelkei nov.sp.: (8) habitus; (9) forebody; (10) head in lateral view; (11) antenna; (12) male abdominal segments VI-VIII; (13-14) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view. Scale bars: 8: 1.0 mm; 9, 11-12: 0.5 mm; 10: 0.2 mm; 13-14: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5276229" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5276229/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="490">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
); punctation fine; microreticulation similar to that of head.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[177,1085,710,820]" pageId="5" pageNumber="490">
Elytra short and distinctly dilated posteriad, approximately 1.2 times as wide and at suture 0.60 times as long as pronotum; humeral angles weakly marked (
<figureCitation box="[923,987,739,761]" captionStart="Figs 8-14" captionStartId="4.[177,217,1480,1502]" captionTargetBox="[181,1071,470,1454]" captionTargetId="figure-203@4.[177,1084,470,1467]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 8-14: Tropimenelytron schuelkei nov.sp.: (8) habitus; (9) forebody; (10) head in lateral view; (11) antenna; (12) male abdominal segments VI-VIII; (13-14) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view. Scale bars: 8: 1.0 mm; 9, 11-12: 0.5 mm; 10: 0.2 mm; 13-14: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5276229" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5276229/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="490">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
); punctation dense and very fine; microreticulation more pronounced than that of head and pronotum. Hind wings reduced. Metatarsomere I slightly longer than II.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[177,1085,835,945]" pageId="5" pageNumber="490">
Abdomen approximately as wide as elytra, widest at segments 
<collectionCode box="[825,844,835,857]" country="Canada" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:13946" name="Royal British Columbia Museum - Herbarium" pageId="5" pageNumber="490" type="Museum">V</collectionCode>
/ 
<collectionCode box="[852,880,835,857]" country="Norway" name="Mykotektet, National Veterinary Institute" pageId="5" pageNumber="490">VI</collectionCode>
; tergites 
<collectionCode box="[974,1026,836,857]" pageId="5" pageNumber="490">III-V</collectionCode>
anteriorly with shallow impression; punctation very fine, sparse on tergites 
<collectionCode box="[928,980,865,886]" pageId="5" pageNumber="490">III-V</collectionCode>
and 
<collectionCode box="[1035,1081,865,886]" pageId="5" pageNumber="490">VIII</collectionCode>
, extremely sparse on tergites VI-VII; posterior margin of tergite 
<collectionCode box="[866,901,895,916]" pageId="5" pageNumber="490">VII</collectionCode>
without palisade fringe.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[177,1085,959,1100]" pageId="5" pageNumber="490">
Ƌ: elytra with pair of posteriorly diverging oblong elevations (
<figureCitation box="[815,877,960,982]" captionStart="Figs 8-14" captionStartId="4.[177,217,1480,1502]" captionTargetBox="[181,1071,470,1454]" captionTargetId="figure-203@4.[177,1084,470,1467]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 8-14: Tropimenelytron schuelkei nov.sp.: (8) habitus; (9) forebody; (10) head in lateral view; (11) antenna; (12) male abdominal segments VI-VIII; (13-14) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view. Scale bars: 8: 1.0 mm; 9, 11-12: 0.5 mm; 10: 0.2 mm; 13-14: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5276229" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5276229/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="490">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
); abdominal tergites III-VI without tubercles; tergite 
<collectionCode box="[511,546,990,1011]" pageId="5" pageNumber="490">VII</collectionCode>
at posterior margin with small median tubercle and with several small granula on either side of tubercle; posterior margin of tergite 
<collectionCode box="[1041,1085,1020,1041]" pageId="5" pageNumber="490">VIII</collectionCode>
truncate and weakly serrate (
<figureCitation box="[478,556,1048,1070]" captionStart="Figs 8-14" captionStartId="4.[177,217,1480,1502]" captionTargetBox="[181,1071,470,1454]" captionTargetId="figure-203@4.[177,1084,470,1467]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 8-14: Tropimenelytron schuelkei nov.sp.: (8) habitus; (9) forebody; (10) head in lateral view; (11) antenna; (12) male abdominal segments VI-VIII; (13-14) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view. Scale bars: 8: 1.0 mm; 9, 11-12: 0.5 mm; 10: 0.2 mm; 13-14: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5276229" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5276229/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="490">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
); posterior margin of sternite 
<collectionCode box="[869,913,1049,1070]" pageId="5" pageNumber="490">VIII</collectionCode>
convex; median lobe of aedeagus as in 
<figureCitation box="[407,520,1078,1100]" captionStart="Figs 8-14" captionStartId="4.[177,217,1480,1502]" captionTargetBox="[181,1071,470,1454]" captionTargetId="figure-203@4.[177,1084,470,1467]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 8-14: Tropimenelytron schuelkei nov.sp.: (8) habitus; (9) forebody; (10) head in lateral view; (11) antenna; (12) male abdominal segments VI-VIII; (13-14) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view. Scale bars: 8: 1.0 mm; 9, 11-12: 0.5 mm; 10: 0.2 mm; 13-14: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5276229" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5276229/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="490">Figs 13-14</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[177,1085,1115,1203]" box="[177,313,1115,1142]" pageId="5" pageNumber="490">
<specimenCount box="[177,198,1119,1142]" pageId="5" pageNumber="490" type="female">♀</specimenCount>
: unknown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[177,1085,1115,1203]" pageId="5" pageNumber="490">
E t y m o l o g y: The species is dedicated to my friend and colleague Michael Schülke, who collected the 
<typeStatus box="[456,548,1181,1203]" pageId="5" pageNumber="490">holotype</typeStatus>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[177,1085,1219,1446]" pageId="5" pageNumber="490">
C o m p a r a t i v e n o t e s a n d s y s t e m a t i c s: The genus 
<taxonomicName box="[915,1085,1219,1241]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Tropimenelytron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="490" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[915,1085,1219,1241]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="490">Tropimenelytron</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was described by 
<bibRefCitation author="PACE R" box="[364,496,1248,1270]" pageId="5" pageNumber="490" pagination="185 - 190" refId="ref11039" refString="PACE R. (1983): Il genere Tropimenelytron SCHEERPELTZ (Coleoptera, Staphylinidae). - Nouvelle Revue d'Entomologie 13: 185 - 190." type="journal article" year="1983">PACE (1983)</bibRefCitation>
, who attributed it to Scheerpeltz, although the latter had not provided a valid description. Several years later, 
<bibRefCitation author="PACE R" box="[832,975,1277,1299]" pageId="5" pageNumber="490" pagination="803 - 863" refId="ref11066" refString="PACE R. (1991): Aleocharinae nepalesi del Museo di Ginevra. Parte V: Athetini (conclusione) e Thamiaraeini (Coleoptera, Staphylinidae). - Revue Suisse de Zoologie 98: 803 - 863." type="journal article" year="1991">PACE (1991)</bibRefCitation>
regarded 
<taxonomicName box="[177,347,1307,1329]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Tropimenelytron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="490" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[177,347,1307,1329]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="490">Tropimenelytron</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a subgenus of 
<taxonomicName authority="KRAATZ 1857" authorityName="KRAATZ" authorityYear="1857" box="[540,802,1307,1329]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Pelioptera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="490" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[540,647,1307,1329]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="490">Pelioptera</emphasis>
KRAATZ 1857
</taxonomicName>
, based on the similar morphology of the ligula and of the ventral aspect of the thorax. 
<bibRefCitation author="GUSAROV V" box="[804,979,1336,1358]" pageId="5" pageNumber="490" pagination="1 - 24" refId="ref10917" refString="GUSAROV V. I. (2002): A revision of Nearctic species of the genus Tropimenelytron PACE, 1983 (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Aleocharinae), a new genus for North America. - Zootaxa 114: 1 - 24." type="journal article" year="2002">GUSAROV (2002)</bibRefCitation>
examined the 
<typeStatus box="[217,261,1366,1387]" pageId="5" pageNumber="490">type</typeStatus>
species and additional representatives of both 
<emphasis box="[748,855,1365,1387]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="490">Pelioptera</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[908,1078,1365,1387]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Tropimenelytron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="490" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[908,1078,1365,1387]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="490">Tropimenelytron</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and reinstated the latter as a distinct genus, a concept tentatively proposed already by ASSING (2000).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[177,1086,1461,1600]" lastBlockId="6.[177,1086,219,416]" lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="491" pageId="5" pageNumber="490">
According to 
<bibRefCitation author="SMETANA A" box="[319,496,1461,1483]" pageId="5" pageNumber="490" pagination="353 - 494" refId="ref11489" refString="SMETANA A. (2004): Staphylinidae, subfamily Aleocharinae, pp. 353 - 494. - In: LOBL I. &amp; A. SMETANA (eds), Catalogue of Palaearctic Coleoptera. II. Hydrophiloidea - Histeroidea - Staphylinoidea. Stenstrup, Apollo Books: 942 pp." type="book chapter" year="2004">SMETANA (2004)</bibRefCitation>
, five species of 
<taxonomicName box="[667,837,1461,1483]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Tropimenelytron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="490" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[667,837,1461,1483]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="490">Tropimenelytron</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were previously known from 
<collectingCountry box="[233,293,1490,1512]" name="China" pageId="5" pageNumber="490">China</collectingCountry>
(
<taxonomicName authority="(PACE 1998)" baseAuthorityName="PACE" baseAuthorityYear="1998" box="[308,550,1490,1512]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Tropimenelytron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="490" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eremita">
<emphasis box="[308,412,1491,1512]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="490">T. eremita</emphasis>
(PACE 1998)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="(PACE 1998)" baseAuthorityName="PACE" baseAuthorityYear="1998" box="[561,856,1490,1512]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Tropimenelytron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="490" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kowloonense">
<emphasis box="[561,719,1490,1512]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="490">T. kowloonense</emphasis>
(PACE 1998)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="(PACE 1998)" baseAuthorityName="PACE" baseAuthorityYear="1998" box="[867,1053,1490,1512]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Tropimenelytron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="490" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lii">
<emphasis box="[867,916,1490,1512]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="490">T. lii</emphasis>
(PACE 1998)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="(PACE 1998))" baseAuthorityName="PACE" baseAuthorityYear="1998" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Tropimenelytron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="490" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="viaticum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="490">T. viaticum</emphasis>
(PACE 1998))
</taxonomicName>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[468,544,1519,1541]" name="Taiwan" pageId="5" pageNumber="490">Taiwan</collectingCountry>
(
<taxonomicName authority="(SMETANA 2004))" authorityName="" baseAuthorityName="SMETANA" baseAuthorityYear="2004" box="[561,842,1519,1541]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Tropimenelytron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="490" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pacei">
<emphasis box="[561,646,1520,1541]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="490">T. pacei</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="SMETANA A" box="[663,826,1519,1541]" pageId="5" pageNumber="490" pagination="353 - 494" refId="ref11489" refString="SMETANA A. (2004): Staphylinidae, subfamily Aleocharinae, pp. 353 - 494. - In: LOBL I. &amp; A. SMETANA (eds), Catalogue of Palaearctic Coleoptera. II. Hydrophiloidea - Histeroidea - Staphylinoidea. Stenstrup, Apollo Books: 942 pp." type="book chapter" year="2004">SMETANA 2004</bibRefCitation>
))
</taxonomicName>
. From the four species recorded from mainland 
<collectingCountry box="[436,499,1549,1571]" name="China" pageId="5" pageNumber="490">China</collectingCountry>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2009" box="[512,636,1549,1571]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Tropimenelytron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="490" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="schuelkei">
<emphasis box="[512,636,1549,1571]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="490">T. schuelkei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is readily separated by external characters alone (much shorter elytra, reduced hind wings, smaller eyes, a more slender head, and paler coloration). From the brachypterous, microphthalmous, and pale-coloured 
<taxonomicName authorityName="" baseAuthorityName="SMETANA" baseAuthorityYear="2004" box="[1003,1086,220,241]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Tropimenelytron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="491" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pacei">
<emphasis box="[1003,1086,220,241]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="491">T. pacei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[234,312,248,270]" name="Taiwan" pageId="6" pageNumber="491">Taiwan</collectingCountry>
, the new species is distinguished by larger size (
<taxonomicName authorityName="" baseAuthorityName="SMETANA" baseAuthorityYear="2004" box="[823,907,249,270]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Tropimenelytron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="491" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pacei">
<emphasis box="[823,907,249,270]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="491">T. pacei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: 
<quantity box="[923,1006,248,270]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.7" pageId="6" pageNumber="491" unit="mm" value="2.7">2.7 mm</quantity>
), larger eyes (in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="" baseAuthorityName="SMETANA" baseAuthorityYear="2004" box="[266,348,278,299]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Tropimenelytron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="491" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pacei">
<emphasis box="[266,348,278,299]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="491">T. pacei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
composed of approximately 15 ommatidia), the much larger and differently shaped elevations on the male elytra, the different modifications of the male tergite 
<collectionCode box="[177,215,336,357]" pageId="6" pageNumber="491">VII</collectionCode>
, and by the slightly different shape of the median lobe of the aedeagus. For illustrations of the four species from the Chinese mainland see 
<bibRefCitation author="PACE R" box="[759,904,365,387]" pageId="6" pageNumber="491" pagination="911 - 982" refId="ref11317" refString="PACE R. (1998 c): Aleocharinae della Cina: Parte IV (Coleoptera, Staphylinidae). - Revue Suisse de Zoologie 105: 911 - 982." type="journal article" year="1998">PACE (1998c)</bibRefCitation>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="" baseAuthorityName="SMETANA" baseAuthorityYear="2004" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Tropimenelytron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="491" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pacei">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="491">Tropimenelytron pacei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is figured (as 
<emphasis box="[377,585,394,416]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="491">Geostibida smetanai</emphasis>
) by 
<bibRefCitation author="PACE R" box="[632,776,394,416]" pageId="6" pageNumber="491" pagination="395 - 463" refId="ref11286" refString="PACE R. (1998 b): Aleocharinae della Cina: Parte II (Coleoptera, Staphylinidae). - Revue Suisse de Zoologie 105: 395 - 463." type="journal article" year="1998">PACE (1998b)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[177,1086,432,571]" pageId="6" pageNumber="491">
D i s t r i b u t i o n a n d b i o n o m i c s: The type locality is situated in the Gaoligong 
<collectingRegion box="[294,347,461,483]" country="Myanmar" name="Shan" pageId="6" pageNumber="491">Shan</collectingRegion>
, to the west of Gongshan in western 
<collectingRegion box="[753,936,461,483]" country="China" name="Yunnan" pageId="6" pageNumber="491">Yunnan province</collectingRegion>
. The adaptive reductions of the eyes, wings, and pigmentation, as well as the altitude of the type locality suggest that the distribution of the species is probably restricted.The 
<typeStatus box="[946,1035,519,541]" pageId="6" pageNumber="491">holotype</typeStatus>
was sifted in a mixed forest at an altitude of 
<quantity box="[582,661,549,571]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.02" pageId="6" pageNumber="491" unit="m" value="3020.0">3020 m</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
